Data scraping and visualization flowMost pagination scrapers die the same way. Someone hardcodes a “last page” number, the site redesigns its pagination three months later, and the script either crashes or silently stops on page 12 forever. I’ve fixed that bug more times than I want to admit. So instead of writing another regex-based page counter, I let Firecrawl figure out when to stop, and it took about 40 lines of code to pull all 1,040 stories off Hacker News.
Here’s the thing about pagination: it exists purely for the user’s benefit. The data isn’t actually limited, it’s just chunked into pages so a browser doesn’t choke loading everything at once. Which means the “last page” isn’t a fixed number, it’s just the first page that comes back empty. Once you stop trying to predict where pagination ends and instead just keep going until it tells you to stop, the whole problem gets a lot simpler.
Want to follow along with your own key? Grab one free at firecrawl.dev — it takes about 30 seconds and no card is required.
Why Pagination Scrapers Usually Break
A scraper that hunts for a “next page” link or a max-page number in the HTML only works as long as that markup stays exactly the same. Change the class name on the pagination widget, switch to infinite scroll, or add a JavaScript-rendered “load more” button, and the whole thing falls over. You end up maintaining brittle selectors that break every time a site ships a redesign, which for anything actively maintained is going to be often.
Firecrawl sidesteps the whole category of problem by handling the rendering and parsing itself and handing you back clean, structured JSON. Since every page returns the same predictable shape, you don’t need to know in advance how many pages exist. You just keep asking for the next one, and the moment a page returns no results, you know you’ve walked off the end. That logic works identically whether the site is static HTML or a JavaScript-heavy single-page app, since Firecrawl renders the page before handing it back.
Scraping One Page Before You Scrape All of Them
Before looping over pages, it’s worth seeing what a single scrape actually returns. Here’s the whole thing in the current Node SDK:
import { Firecrawl } from "firecrawl";const app = new Firecrawl({ apiKey: "fc-YOUR_API_KEY" });
const result = await app.scrape("https://news.ycombinator.com");
console.log(result);
Run that and you get the page back as markdown by default, which includes every story, but also every bit of surrounding noise, nav links, footer text, “hide” and “flag” buttons, none of which you actually want. That’s fine for a quick look, but not what you’d want to build a pipeline around.
That’s four lines to pull a live web page into your code with zero proxy setup, no headless browser to manage, and no HTML to parse by hand. If you’re used to wiring up Puppeteer or Playwright yourself, this is the part where you notice how much you’re no longer maintaining. Test it against your own target site for free at firecrawl.dev.
Getting Only What You Actually Want With a JSON Schema
Swap the output format to JSON and hand Firecrawl a schema describing exactly what you want back, and it strips out everything else:
import { Firecrawl } from "firecrawl";
import { z } from "zod";const app = new Firecrawl({ apiKey: "fc-YOUR_API_KEY" });
const schema = z.object({
stories: z.array(
z.object({
title: z.string(),
url: z.string(),
points: z.number(),
comments: z.number(),
})
),
});
const result = await app.scrape("https://news.ycombinator.com", {
formats: [{ type: "json", schema, prompt: "Extract each story's title, URL, points, and comment count" }],
});
console.log(result.json.stories);
This is the part that saves the most time once you’re working with real sites instead of demos: no cleanup pass, no post-processing script to strip navigation and ads out of scraped markdown. If you’ve got a page you’ve been meaning to turn into structured data, sign up at firecrawl.dev and try this exact schema pattern against it.
Walking Every Page Until It Tells You to Stop
This is the actual pagination logic, and it’s simpler than most people expect. Hacker News pages are predictable, ?p=1, ?p=2, and so on, so you don't need to discover the URL pattern, just increment it. The loop keeps scraping, pushing results into an array, and bumping the page number, until a scrape comes back with an empty stories array:
import { Firecrawl } from "firecrawl";
import { z } from "zod";
import fs from "fs";const app = new Firecrawl({ apiKey: "fc-YOUR_API_KEY" });
const schema = z.object({
stories: z.array(
z.object({
title: z.string(),
url: z.string(),
points: z.number(),
comments: z.number(),
})
),
});
let page = 1;
const allStories = [];
while (true) {
const result = await app.scrape(`https://news.ycombinator.com/news?p=${page}`, {
formats: [{ type: "json", schema, prompt: "Extract each story's title, URL, points, and comment count" }],
});
const rows = result.json?.stories ?? [];
if (rows.length === 0) break;
const withPageNumber = rows.map((row) => ({ ...row, page }));
allStories.push(...withPageNumber);
page += 1;
}
fs.writeFileSync("hn-stories.json", JSON.stringify(allStories, null, 2));
console.log(`Done. Scraped ${allStories.length} stories across ${page - 1} pages.`);
That’s the entire scraper. Run it and it walks every page on Hacker News, tagging each story with the page number it came from, until it hits a page with nothing on it and stops on its own. When I let this run, it climbed all the way to page 61 before coming back empty, which put the final count at just over 1,040 stories, all written to a single JSON file with zero manual page-counting.
The part worth noticing is what isn’t in this code: no hardcoded max page, no try/catch around a “did the layout change” check, no separate logic for “what if this site switches to infinite scroll.” The stopping condition is just “did I get anything back,” which holds regardless of how the site’s pagination is implemented under the hood.
This entire loop, all 1,040 stories across 61 pages, ran comfortably inside Firecrawl’s free tier. If you’ve got a paginated site you’ve been putting off scraping because the “how do I know when to stop” problem felt annoying to solve, this is the whole solution, and it costs nothing to try at firecrawl.dev.
Taking This Further
Once you’ve got the raw JSON file, you can drop it straight into a research agent, feed it into a CI pipeline that tracks trending topics over time, or wrap the whole loop as a reusable skill your agent calls whenever it needs fresh paginated data. The pattern isn’t specific to Hacker News. Swap the URL, the schema, and the prompt, and the same while-loop works for product listings, job boards, or review pages, anywhere content is split across numbered pages.
If your target site doesn’t use page numbers at all and instead loads more content on scroll, the loop above won’t apply directly, since there’s no URL to increment. That’s what Firecrawl’s Interact endpoint is for: it drives a real browser session that can scroll, click “load more,” and read what just rendered, the same structured-output approach applied to a page that never gives you a new URL to ask for. Both endpoints live under the same firecrawl.dev account, so switching between them is a code change, not a new signup.
